[SN]TITLE[SN]
Six Nations travel warning ahead of Wales v Ireland

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
Visitors to Cardiff are being urged to plan ahead as a sell-out crowd of 74,000 is expected at the Principality Stadium on Friday night.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
There has been several miles of stop-start traffic on the M4 approaching Newport's Brynglas Tunnels since late afternoon.
Some roads will be closed in the city centre from 18:00 GMT to 23:00 as Wales take on Ireland in the Six Nations.
Local buses will be diverted away from city centre bus stops.
And a queuing system will be in place at Cardiff Central rail station with shoppers advised to use the park and ride.
Arriva Trains Wales said all services into Cardiff would be "extremely busy throughout the day" and advised rugby fans to arrive at least three hours before kick-off.
It said all available trains would be in service, with thousands of extra spaces provided.
However, services will be "extremely limited" after 22:00 and customers should return directly to Cardiff Central station after the game.
The match kicks off at 20:05.
The following road closures will be in place:
The following roads will be closed in their entirety: Duke Street, Castle Street, High Street, St Mary Street, Caroline Street, Wood Street, Central Square, Westgate Street, Quay Street, Guildhall Place, Golate, Park Street, Havelock Street and Scott Road.
